<TEXT>
a dispute with promoters prompted the rap group 2 
live crew to cancel a concert triggering a melee by unruly fans 
that injured two newspaper photographers and a reporter 
the rappers whose album as nasty as they wanna be has been 
ruled obscene by a florida judge and banned in san antonio refused 
to play saturday night at the longhorn ballroom after a promoter 
refused to pay them in advance 
shortly afterward about 50 people went on a rampage breaking 
chairs and throwing bottles 
security guards forced the protesters outside but several 
windows in the front of the building were broken and some cars were 
vandalized before about 50 police in riot gear arrived and 
dispersed the crowd witnesses said 
the ruckus lasted about 12 minutes 
dallas times herald photographers jesse hornbuckle and cedric 
thompson assigned to cover the concert were treated for minor 
injuries at methodist medical center in dallas early sunday 
reporter mindy donnelly was hit in the head and lost a tooth cap 
but didnt require treatment 
hornbuckle said up to 10 fans attacked him as he attempted to 
photograph a smaller group attacking thompson cameras and other 
equipment belonging to both photographers were destroyed by the 
fans 
hornbuckle salvaged one roll of film and his picture of a fan 
being restrained by guards appeared in one edition of sundays 
times herald 
a car belonging to another herald reporter was vandalized the 
fans also smashed the windshield of a kxastv remote broadcast van 
bob lowder a spokesman at the longhorn referred all inquiries 
about the payment dispute and possible refunds to the shows 
promoters they promoters did not return telephone calls sunday 
lowder said a damage estimate wasnt immediately available but 
he said crews had cleaned up most of the mess in time for an aids 
benefit at the club sunday afternoon 
2 live crew performed sunday night at the club xs in austin 
with a clean concert at 7 pm and an unexpurgated show set 
for 11 pm for fans age 21 and over the 860seat club was sold 
out for the late show said promoter jerry latouf 
about 10 picketers from the american family association gathered 
in front of the austin club they carried placards denouncing the 
groups explicit lyrics 
the group held up signs reading 2 lewd crew and women are 
not sexual toys they also chanted 2 live crew too obscene 
band leader luther campbell asked the mostly male crowd of about 
150 people if they had seen the protesters outside and then read 
off an obscene message he asked the crowd to deliver them on their 
way out 
latouf said the group was paid in full before the first show 
thats standard operating procedure in the entertainment 
business latouf said you pay the group half of their money 
when you book them and the other half 10 minutes before they go on 
stage 
i cant imagine not paying a band before they go on he said 
</TEXT>
