a fire burning for three 
days in yellowstone national park spread across 220 acres on 
saturday but officials were confident it could soon be fully 
contained 
by saturday night firefighters had contained about 60 percent 
of the lightningcaused blaze in the parks northeastern section 
and expected to have it fully under control by monday evening said 
park spokeswoman marsha karle 
we dont expect it to move anymore she said it may burn 
back on itself but unless the winds increase or humidity drops 
dramatically it looks like its not going anywhere we almost have 
a line all the way around it 
about 315 firefighters were deployed to battle the parks first 
major blaze of the summer karle said ground crews were helped by 
drops of fire retardant and water from helicopters and airplanes 
over the lower east slopes of mount washburn and by cooler 
temperatures and light winds she said 
crews have had difficulty gauging the parameters of the fire 
which started thursday afternoon and had spread to an estimated 100 
acres by late friday she said 
its been very smoky and hard to see karle said its 
been hard to get real good fix because the terrain is steep rocky 
and hard to get around no structures have been threatened but a 
couple of hiking trails in the area were closed 
