<TEXT>
the bush administration is determined to resolve 
a nasty dispute between the united states and europe over farm 
subsidies at this years economic summit 
without a compromise on agriculture the administration 
believes an ambitious fouryear effort to overhaul the global 
trading system could end in failure 
those talks being held under the auspices of the 97nation 
general agreement on tariffs and trade hold out tremendous promise 
of expanding trade opportunities for american farmers and 
businesses by removing existing barriers and bringing more products 
under the rules of the global trading system 
in an era when the united states has suffered through six 
consecutive years of 100 billionplus trade deficits it is no 
wonder that the administration is searching for ways to boost us 
exports 
us trade representative carla hills paints failure of the 
trade liberalization talks in almost apocalyptic terms of gravely 
diminished prosperity for both rich and poor nations alike as 
countries turn inward and erect trade barriers 
the talks known as the uruguay round for the country where they 
began in 1986 face an endoftheyear deadline for conclusion with 
the final bargaining session scheduled for brussels in early 
december however with only six months left none of the major 
issues has been resolved 
us negotiators are seeking to phase out all tradedistorting 
farm subsidies to dismantle barriers to trade in services a 
highgrowth area where the united states is extremely competitive 
and to crack down on copyright piracy estimated to cost american 
companies 60 billion annually 
but of all the issues agriculture is seen as the key that is 
because third world countries have balked at agreeing to us 
proposals on removing barriers to trade in services and beefing up 
their enforcement of copyright laws unless they win expanded 
markets for their farm products 
the farm subsidy battle is also draining government treasuries 
with the cost to us taxpayers and consumers put at 75 billion 
annually and the cost to the 12nation european community running 
an even higher 125 billion annually 
the united states is pushing for a complete phase out of 
subsidies in three areas export subsidies paid by governments to 
make their countrys products cheaper on world markets domestic 
price supports paid to farmers to boost production and barriers 
erected to keep products out thus boosting the price to a 
countrys consumers 
the european community however has balked at this approach 
expressing a willingness only to consider reducing the aggregate 
total of farm subsidies and charging that the us proposals could 
mean pushing 2 million to 3 million of their lessefficient farmers 
off the land a politically unacceptable result 
the dispute over farm subsidies turned bitter at a may session 
attended by us and european officials 
frans andriessen the communitys top trade official told 
reporters in houston that continued pressure by the united states 
would backfire and make it even harder to reach a compromise 
if the pressure is exaggerated it makes it more difficult to 
negotiate andriessen said 
the united states however is holding firm to its position that 
it will accept nothing less than an agreement which addresses all 
three areas 
the bush administration has tried to paint the european 
community as the lone holdout in the farm battle but japan is also 
holding back on the question of removing all market barriers which 
would submit the protected japanese rice market to foreign 
competition 
about the only thing that is certain is that bush will have his 
hands full in convincing his economic summit partners to come 
around to the us position japan west germany france britain 
and italy all have reasons for protecting farm subsidies at the 
economic summit bush can count only on canadian prime minister 
brian mulroney for full support for the us position 
but hills said the united states has no intention of dropping 
its effort for global agricultural reform seeing success here as 
the key to achieving ultimate victory with the total uruguay round 
the uruguay round holds the promise at a magical moment in 
history of being the ultimate competitiveness machine it will 
provide an enormous boost for emerging democracies in eastern 
europe and latin america she told reporters at a presummit 
briefing it holds a real prize not only for us but for the 
vitality of the global trading system in the 21st century 
