<TEXT>
just eight days before georgias primary 
elections a federal judge will hear arguments monday in a lawsuit 
alleging that the states majorityvote rule is racially 
discriminatory 
a group of black legislators and civil rights officials led by 
state rep tyrone brooks has challenged the system that requires a 
runoff if one candidate fails to receive a majority of the votes 
cast in elections for state offices 
the class action suit seeks to immediately impose a plurality 
system whereby the candidate receiving the most votes would be the 
winner even if he or she got fewer than half a hearing is 
scheduled before us district judge richard c freeman 
if imposed before the primary such a method would be seen as 
helping former atlanta mayor andrew young in his bid against four 
others in the democratic gubernatorial race 
young trying to become georgias first black governor is 
thought to have a better chance to win a plurality on july 17 than 
a majority in a twocandidate runoff current polls put him roughly 
equal with the leading white candidate with each getting about 30 
percent support 
young however is not backing the lawsuit 
the state has argued that the 1964 law passed in the wake of 
national civil rights legislation was not rooted in racism but 
instead represents a longstanding commitment to the concept of 
majority voting 
attorney general michael bowers chraged in briefs filed last 
month that the suit was an attempt to manipulate the 
governors race 
laughlin mcdonald an american civil liberties union attorney 
representing the plaintiffs in the case said he will present 
evidence that the georgia system was established as a way to 
maintain the power of the states white democratic leadership and 
disenfranchise blacks 
the white democratic leadership regards it as very 
critical he said friday if you go to a plurality it will 
drive out the white majority 
lawyers in the attorney generals office who are involved in the 
suit did not return phone calls for comment late last week 
brooks said friday that legislative debate at the time of the 
bills passage focused on its impact on blacks and that the 
results of elections in ensuing years have provided ample evidence 
that the majority requirement discourages black candidates 
were going to do our best to demonstrate to judge freeman 
that when the statute was enacted the intent was to keep blacks out 
of office brooks said 
we intend to show that because of the runoff weve been kept 
at the bare minimum of the elected officials he said 
brooks brushed aside criticism that the suit was timed to aid 
young he said he has been trying to eliminate the runoff system 
since 1984 but has been turned back by his fellow lawmakers 
no matter when you file it its going to impact on some 
election cycle brooks said we have elections every two years 
we didnt see any reason not to file it this year 
mcdonald rejected the notion that the concept of majority voting 
was an american tradition 
to say that it is american and constitutional is simply not 
so he said the bill of rights says that minorities do have 
rights 
