<TEXT>
albanian leader ramiz alia appears 
unshaken in his determination to keep tight control over his 
limited reform program despite unprecedented popular resistance to 
decades of harsh communist rule 
the crisis began when thousands of discontented albanians 
crowded foreign embassies hoping for a chance to begin new lives in 
the west others took to the streets of the capital tirana in 
antigovernment protests 
but by sunday the turmoil generated by the asylumseekers had 
not escalated into the kind of unrest that toppled communists 
elsewhere in europe 
potentially more threatening to the regime was dissatisfaction 
with its slow tentative approach to changing the centrally 
controlled economy which has caused albanias standard of living 
to lag far behind its neighbors 
alia began tinkering with the stalinist economic political and 
social systems he inherited even before the rush on foreign 
embassies in tirana 
under a reform program begun in may and recently accelerated 
citizens who previously had no hope of traveling abroad are now 
entitled to passports a ban on religion has been lifted the death 
penalty has been abolished for defectors and modest economic 
retooling has been promised 
the country long considered the hermit of europe for its 
isolationist policies has signaled willingness to restore ties 
with both superpowers it plans to join the 35nation conference on 
security and cooperation in europe after being the only nation on 
the continent to boycott it 
but alia has offered far fewer reforms than communists in other 
eastern european countries such as hungary and bulgaria who 
voluntarily abolished their monopoly on power and introduced 
multiparty democracies 
alia told a special session of the communist party central 
committee called in part to deal with the embassy crisis that the 
party would remain supreme 
what is of fundamental importance is the fact that the masses 
should be led by the party alia told the meeting over the 
weekend his comments avoided any reference to even limited 
political plurality 
while the central committee approved personnel changes in the 
party and government alias authority appeared unshaken several 
longtime politburo members were replaced with younger men believed 
closer to his way thinking 
the naming of hekuran isai as interior and police minister 
however seemed to indicate a determination to deal harshly with 
any challenge from the street of the kind that ended communist rule 
in romania czechoslovakia and east germany 
isai had held the post under enver hoxha the founder of 
communist albania and alias predecessor the choice disappointed 
those hoping for central committee appointees not associated with 
past repression 
police sealed off embassy row over the weekend from new 
asylumseekers but it appeared they had been ordered to keep a low 
profile and avoid further street confrontations as the leadership 
sought to weather the storm 
as part of that strategy authorities agreed saturday to let the 
more than 5000 asylumseekers emigrate under foreign supervision 
the leaders clearly hoped that sealing the embassy district and 
providing free access to passports would halt another rush on the 
diplomatic missions and end the threat of unrest 
alia also announced limited economic reforms to the central 
committee meeting calculated to alleviate low living standards 
lack of luxury items and shortages of staples all of which have 
generated widespread dissatisfaction 
he announced wage increases of as high as 20 percent in some 
cases and said tradesmen and shopkeepers could once again work for 
themselves rather than the state such moves may be too little too 
late however particularly under liberalized travel laws allowing 
more of the population of 32 million to compare their spartan 
existence to life in the west 
while some of the asylumseekers appeared motivated by 
frustration over political repression others were clearly 
disillusioned by their scramble to make ends meet and ready to risk 
all for a better economic life 
one of the wouldbe emigres in a telephone interview with 
hungarian state radio said he just cant make a living in 
albania 
the 28yearold man said he worked as bricklayer a chauffeur 
and a lathe operator for 60 dollars a month not enough to 
support his family 
