<TEXT>
soviet president mikhail s gorbachev is worried 
his country cannot make the painful leap from a closely controlled 
economic system to a marketdriven version without western help 
his quest for financial aid will be a major issue at the 
sevennation summit of industrial powers that opens monday in 
houston 
but its a twopart issue not only is there the question of how 
much the other industrial giants can or want to do but also the 
matter of what a huge cash infusion would accomplish in the soviet 
union 
there is no doubt gorbachev wants help he has made that clear 
in public as well as in recent private letters to president bush 
and british prime minister margaret thatcher 
the leaders of west germany and france are advocating that the 
industrial powers approve aid worth 15 billion to bolster reforms 
and help moscow meet payments to foreign firms the soviet union 
traditionally has been punctual in meeting payments but recent 
delays have started to erode confidence among foreign investors 
bonn already has approved an unconditional loan of 31 billion 
and chancellor helmut kohl is apparently growing impatient with 
opposition from other leaders to the soviet aid plan 
bush so far has been reluctant to agree to a massive aid program 
until soviet authorities move more decisively from a planned to a 
market economy 
estimates of how much money would begin to stabilize the soviet 
economy range from 5 billion to 20 billion colossal compared to 
what eastern european countries have received to restructure their 
economies but modest given the size of the soviet economy and its 
relatively small foreign debt 
moscows balanceofpayment deficit now tops 2 billion nearly 
half it owed to west german companies part of the west german 
credit is expected to be used to pay overdue bills 
inability to keep food stores stocked has already forced moscow 
to spend an extra 3 billion rubles 500 million on food imports 
and more aid is thought necessary if the soviet union is going 
to leap from a centrally planned to a market economy 
without western cash the move to the market could inflict 
hardship on the population and more social pressure on gorbachev 
premier nikolai i ryzhkov told the supreme soviet parliament in 
late may that the consumer market was destitute 
ryzhkov presenting a plan for what he called a regulated 
market economy warned that if trends continued many crucial 
decisions unpopular as they are will meet an even more embittered 
response 
the soviet economy is plagued by inflation and a huge budget 
deficit in the first four months of this year ethnic unrest and 
strikes caused the loss of an estimated 10 million manhours 
promarket reforms are likely to drop production further as 
unprofitable businesses go bankrupt 
still there is hope that western aid could help keep store 
shelves stocked and bolster peoples faith that reforms will 
improve their lives 
soviet reformers are stymied not only by consumer shortages but 
by a 70year legacy of central planning that allowed only limited 
forms of individual enterprise they are also hampered by decades 
of propaganda portraying capitalist economies as ridden with 
poverty unemployment and vicious competition 
gosplan the central agency responsible for running the economy 
has concluded outside aid is needed but has not made public a 
blueprint for how to spend western money 
delegates to the 28th communist party congress under way in 
moscow have shown deep hostility to private property and individual 
ownership of factories although some delegates did support western 
help 
aid is a good idea there are big changes in our economy but 
we cant seem to set things straight help could make things better 
and we should accept this offer said delegate nikolai v mikhug 
a worker from a tuberolling factory in the ural mountains 
