<TEXT>
a test found the national weather services new 
computerized radar storm detection system breaks down frequently 
and is less reliable than the 33yearold system now in use a 
newspaper reported sunday 
results of the sixmonth test rate the 1957vintage radar system 
as 10 times more reliable than the new equipment called nexrad 
the cleveland plain dealer reported sunday 
the test results were obtained under the freedom of information 
act by the union representing weather service employees the 
national weather service employees organization it said 
the test was conducted by the air force from march to august 
1989 in oklahoma the 118page report said the new radar 
malfunctioned every 19 days while the existing radar called 
wsr57 breaks down on average every 14 days 
the air force testers said failures critically degraded the 
effectiveness of nexrad because they occurred during periods when 
forecasters especially depend upon radar to detect severe storm 
patterns 
many times in severe weather episodes when the operators 
needed the system to support critical warning operations the 
system was not available the air force said 
the testers said the wsr57 has a demonstrated reliability 
approximately 10 times greater than the demonstrated reliability of 
the nexrad tested 
some 120 nexrad units which can measure wind speed and 
direction and rain volume in a storm are the centerpiece of a 1 
billion modernization of the weather service scheduled for the 
1990s 
william read head of a team investigating the weather services 
actions during the june 14 storm that caused flash flooding in 
eastern ohio and killed 26 said the conventional radar at 
akroncanton was unable to determine the storms severity in time 
to post a warning 
don sarreals special assistant to the nexrad program office 
said the weather service is committed to modernization despite the 
test results 
the program is supported and we are proceeding to install the 
radar sarreals said were making progress as rapidly as we 
can when youre building something for the first time you 
encounter various obstacles 
he said the first operational nexrad will be installed in 
october near oklahoma city 
its going to go through a vigorous testing period before its 
turned over to the government and commissioned sarreals said 
most problems have been encountered in the computers that 
interpret weather data obtained by the radar unit he said 
the key to the thing is the computer thats what makes it 
unique sarreals said its the computer that can dig into the 
data 
in the eastern ohio flooding meteorologists were unable to 
determine the potential rainfall in the thunderstorms appearing on 
conventional radar sarreals said 
you have to make estimates for rainfall now which are 
basically done by humans he said a computer with a highspeed 
processor will dig into that with nexrad 
