<TEXT>
the united states undisputed leader of the free 
world for four decades of cold war is adjusting to a new era when 
economic power counts more than military might 
the adjustment process will be nowhere more apparent than in 
houston as president bush plays host beginning monday for the 
annual economic summit meeting of the worlds seven richest 
industrial democracies 
where the western allies were once willing to let the united 
states set the agenda the summit countries seem willing even 
eager to chart their own courses now that americas nuclear 
umbrella no longer seems crucial 
1990 is the first year after the end of the cold war said 
michael mandelbaum an international expert with the council on 
foreign relations it is a time when the american nuclear surplus 
will be less and less important and the american fiscal deficit 
will be more important 
america is still the wealthiest of the wealthy when measured in 
terms of the 5 trillion in goods and services it produces 
annually but japan now second with a 3 trillion economy has 
been rapidly closing the gap some economists believe it could 
surpass the united states by the year 2000 
japan has already replaced the united states as the worlds 
largest creditor country reflecting its global investment clout 
america which began the 1980s as the worlds largest creditor 
country is now the biggest debtor the transformation occurred 
largely because americans transferred billions of dollars into 
foreign hands to pay for imported cars television sets and other 
consumer goods 
forced now to rely on foreigners to finance its economy to the 
tune of about 10 billion a month the new economic reality has 
spurred great domestic debate over whether the united states is 
losing control of its destiny to foreigners 
bush finds himself at odds with a number of the summit countries 
on a variety of issues at this years summit ranging from aid to 
the soviet union to cleaning up the global environment and trying 
to keep a nasty battle over farm subsidies from scuttling an effort 
to reform the world trading system 
if the farm subsidy fight is not resolved some analysts fear 
that the cold war could very well be followed by a global trade war 
as more and more countries fall to squabbling over trade imbalances 
and erect protectionist barriers to keep imports out 
as the compelling drive of the soviet threat no long forces 
the west to work together the economic forces could drive them 
apart said robert hormats a vice president at goldman sachs and 
a former us sherpa the top aide who prepares the summit 
agenda for the president 
the huge us budget deficit has long been a sore point with 
americas summit partners who contend that americas profligate 
borrowing needs have driven up world interest rates now that us 
defense spending is no longer seen as critical to keeping world 
peace the size of the budget deficit is likely to be even more of 
an irritant 
just before the summit bush reversed his opposition to tax 
increases as a way of solving the deficit problem while that 
change of heart drew catcalls from conservatives in the united 
states many foreign officials have breathed a sigh of relief 
they view getting the us budget under control as a critical 
step in solving some of americas more nettlesome economic problems 
as well as providing bush with sorely needed resources to play a 
more active role on the world stage 
last year for the first time japan replaced the united states 
as the worlds largest donor of official foreign aid 
the us government constrained by the budget deficit has 
provided what many considered to be rather modest amounts to help 
in the economic transformation of former communist countries in 
europe 
some foreign leaders see americas budget problems as the real 
reason bush is dragging his feet on giving direct economic support 
for soviet president mikhail s gorbachevs reform efforts 
bush is coming to the summit with one new initiative seeking 
support from the other leaders for a us plan to pour economic aid 
into fledgling democracies in latin america similar to the 
assistance being offered former communist countries in europe 
that bush proposal has been seen as a hopeful sign that the 
united states while no longer able to dominate the economic 
agenda will not draw inward in the coming decade 
our credibility has been damaged by unwillingness to provide 
even modest resources to support democratization in eastern europe 
and latin america said c fred bergsten head of the institute 
for international economics a washingtonbased research group 
budget correction would enable the united states to become a 
serious global player and world leader again 
