voters in warscarred chad cast ballots 
sunday in the first contested election since independence in 1960 
but opposition parties remain banned and virtually all candidates 
were from the ruling party 
voters chose among 436 progovernment candidates for the 123 
seats in a new national assembly most were from the ruling 
national union for independence and the revolution 
democracy here we are declared an enthusiastic commentator 
on state radio which reported calm orderly voting throughout the 
country 
some polling stations in ndjamena the capital were reported 
crowded and others nearly deserted as chads 3 million eligible 
voters had their first opportunity to pick among political rivals 
although opposition parties were barred from the elections the 
campaign was lively and hardfought candidates toured city streets 
in vehicles equipped with loudspeakers and wooed voters with offers 
of lowpriced beer or free sugar in one ndjamena district 26 
candidates were competing 
the 4000 polling stations spread across the vast landlocked 
nation opened at 6 am local time and were scheduled to close at 
midnight final results were not expected for at least two days 
the elections are the product of constitutional reforms approved 
by 99 percent of the electorate in a dec 10 referendum that also 
gave president hissene habre another sevenyear term 
habre voted about in his ndjamena neighborhood then told 
journalists that chad was entering a phase of democratization 
i hope these processes will be seen through to completion 
he said 
of the 123 assembly seats five are reserved for women and will 
be allocated on a delayed basis if less than five women win seats 
outright assembly members will serve fiveyear terms 
few senior members of the government or ruling party are seeking 
seats in the assembly which will replace the recently dissolved 
national consultative council 
the council had served as national legislature since 1982 but 
its members were appointed by habre and its powers were limited 
some council members have questioned whether the new assembly will 
have greater authority 
the threeweek campaign ended without any reports of serious 
political violence although the statecontrolled press scolded 
some candidates for wooing support with gifts or emphasizing clan 
allegiances rather than issues 
chad has a population of about 55 million it is one of the 
worlds poorest countries with an annual per capita income of 
200 and has been engaged in civil war almost continuously since 
independence from france three decades ago 
habres government is locked in a struggle with libyanbacked 
rebels who stage raids on border outposts from neighboring sudan 
the only previous legislative elections in chad were in 1962 
but the ruling party put up only one candidate for each seat 
