<TEXT>
us officials helped at least 39 people 
including exnazis slip into canada to build a new life in the 
early 1950s to reward them for their work as spies previously 
classified documents indicate 
a study by ottawa historian alti rodal completed three years 
ago for a federal royal commission that investigated suspected nazi 
war criminals says the 39 people came to canada with false 
documents and identities from us authorities 
ms rodals report was released in heavily censored form in 
1987 with several general references to the involvement by us 
intelligence officers in resettling alleged exnazis 
the report said the us officials who were responsible for 
screening europeans seeking a new life in north america after the 
war misled canadian authorities about the backgrounds of some of 
the emigrants 
the 39 cases involved mostly germans who had worked for nazi 
organizations during world war ii they were recruited by the 
united states after 1945 as part of an intelligence ring to spy on 
the russian zone of occupied germany and suspected communist 
sympathizers in the american zone 
more details of the resettlement plan emerged last week as 
material previously deleted from ms rodals report was made public 
following requests by journalists under the access to information 
act 
there was no cia spokesperson available sunday in washington to 
comment on the new details from ms rodals report 
government documents cited by ms rodal show the royal canadian 
mounted police and the external affairs department were surprised 
when they stumbled on the us plan in 195354 
lester pearson then external affairs minister and future 
liberal prime minister complained the americans should have taken 
such people into their own country if they wanted them rather than 
dumping them on others 
canadian diplomats in washington were instructed to take the 
matter up directly with allen dulles then head of the cia 
washington eventually provided background information on the 
people involved and assured external affairs the information 
package was complete 
but royal police memos indicate the police force was skeptical 
and thought others may have been smuggled in and never detected 
one memo from september 1954 noted 35 cases had been discussed 
at that point with the americans but we are not convinced that 
the figures which have been given to us in the first instance are 
in fact correct 
another memo the same month noted four more cases had been 
discovered 
all involved people were sponsored by the us army research and 
resettlement branch which played a key role in relocating former 
intelligence agents including nazi collaborators 
ms rodal concluded the americans probably acted with the 
knowledge and cooperation of a royal police sergeant then 
stationed in karlsruhe west germany he apparently kept the scheme 
from his superior 
at least some had criminal records on grounds of moral turpitude 
the immigration category then used to exclude suspected war 
criminals and nazi collaborators 
the 198587 royal commission under justice jules deschenes 
recommended urgent action against 20 suspected war criminals in 
canada and further investigation of 200 other cases 
the justice department has since initiated three criminal 
prosecutions and one civil action it has 45 other cases under 
consideration 
