<TEXT>
wine consumption in the us dropped 
sharply for the second straight year in 1989 with mississippians 
drinking the least and tipplers in the district of columbia the 
most a trade publication reported 
drinkers in california new york and washington the top three 
wineproducing states drank the most wine per capita but new 
hampshire was the only state to show a gain in consumption over 
1988 according to wines amp vines 
americans last year drank 211 gallons of wine per capita the 
lowest consumption of any major wineproducing nation and a 58 
percent drop from 1988 consumption in 1988 dropped 5 percent from 
1987 figures 
by comparison americans over 21 drank 337 gallons of beer 
216 gallons of distilled spirits and about 35 gallons of coffee 
adultonly wine consumption was 303 gallons per capita 
reflecting a national trend against alcohol consumption 
individual states posted figures showing as much as a 195 percent 
drop from 1988 that distinction went to arizona where a 
halfgallon less of wine per capita was consumed last year than in 
1988 
the domestic wine market including imports fell 52 percent to 
523 million gallons it was a 641 million gallon drop from a high 
point of 5871 million gallons in 1986 the report said 
domestic table wines fell 26 percent while production of 
domestic champagnes dropped 63 percent last year marked the 
fourth straight year of decline for foreign champagne sales in this 
country they were down 78 percent to 12 million gallons 
in 1985 champagne imports to the united states hit a peak of 
158 million gallons almost all of it from italy france and spain 
california wines accounted for 728 percent of all wine consumed 
in the us last year while the other 42 wineproducing states 
held 126 percent of the market the rest of the market 146 
percent were imports 
wines amp vines blamed the market drop on the continuing loss of 
ground of generic or jug wines nearly all of it produced in 
californias san joaquin valley and a 167 percent dip in wine 
cooler sales 
it was the second doubledigit loss in two years for the 
coolers sales phenomenon of the early 1980s that literally rescued 
california wine for several years in 1988 and 1989 cooler sales 
fell 333 million gallons falling from 21 percent of wine market 
share to 17 percent last year 
still the coolers mostly cheap white wine fruit juice and 
carbonated water represented one of six gallons of wine sold in 
this country last year 
there were at least three bright spots for the industry 
including a relatively weak us dollar and its builtin price 
advantage over imports 
blush varietals such as white zinfandel and white grenache 
prime fuels for the top selling white wine segment continued to 
gain market share while the booming premiums which cost over 3 a 
standard bottle increased 7 percent at a slower rate than 
previous postings 
us wine exports were up again in 1989 showing foreign sales 
increased to a miniscule 221 million gallons in 1989 from 169 
gallons in 1988 the top two markets are canada 57 million 
gallons and japan 55 million gallons 
